{"ts":"2026-06-27T22:59:23.617Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"tool","toolName":"read_files","toolCallId":"bp840y7n","output":[{"query":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/docs/PHASE_5_MVP_BACKEND.md","result":"  1 | # GFF AI Platform: Phase 5 Local MVP Backend Setup & Developer Guide\n  2 | \n  3 | This document establishes the strategic, technical, and operational manual for configuring and running the **Phase 5 Local MVP Backend** of the GFF AI Platform. \n  4 | \n  5 | To support the premium, high-fidelity presentation layer developed in Phase 4, Phase 5 introduces a lightweight, high-performance local FastAPI backend. This local server connects to a local SQLite database, processes authentications via JSON Web Tokens (JWT), and hosts multi-tenant workspaces so that developers and stakeholders can test complete client and administrative flows locally.\n  6 | \n  7 | ---\n  8 | \n  9 | ## 1. Executive Narrative & Architectural Scope\n 10 | \n 11 | ### 1.1. Decoupled Sandbox Metaphor\n 12 | In alignment with the GFF AI **Sovereign Operating System** philosophy, the Phase 5 backend is engineered as a local developer sandbox. It replicates multi-tenant access control and core database persistence without introducing complex, expensive production dependencies. \n 13 | \n 14 | This local engine acts as the \"State Synchronizer\" for the frontend cockpit, enabling real-time REST API handshakes, dynamic database logging, and role-based clearance verification.\n 15 | \n 16 | ### 1.2. Scope & Boundaries (MVP Development Phase)\n 17 | The Phase 5 backend is designed **exclusively for local development, demonstration, and offline evaluation**. It provides a solid architectural foundation while intentionally omitting several enterprise cloud-scale features.\n 18 | \n 19 | > ⚠️ **Phase Scope Limitations**:\n 20 | > *   **Local-Only Database**: Uses a local SQLite file (`dev.db`). No RDS/Postgres database setups are used.\n 21 | > *   **No AWS Integrations**: Does not utilize real AWS resources (such as DynamoDB, S3 file buckets, or AWS IAM roles).\n 22 | > *   **No Storage Backend**: File uploads and secure legal document storage are handled via frontend-only simulation placeholders; no physical file-saving backend is active.\n 23 | > *   **No External Payment Gateways**: Computational \"Epoch\" invoicing and billing tables exist in SQLite, but there is no integration with billing aggregators like Stripe or Chargebee.\n 24 | > *   **No Real Emails/OTP/SSO**: There is no live SMTP mailer, Multi-Factor/One-Time Password (OTP) verification, or OAuth2/SSO identity providers. Auth relies strictly on standard OAuth2 JWT tokens with local bcrypt hashing.\n 25 | > *   **No Live Backend for GFF AI Tools**: Tool execution engines, prompt generators, and agent configurations run within mock sandboxes inside the frontend client.\n 26 | > *   **No Production Auth Hardening**: Features like Rate-limiting, IP-restrictions, secure HttpOnly cookie session management, or Hardware Security Module (HSM) signing are deferred to production deployment phases.\n 27 | \n 28 | ---\n 29 | \n 30 | ## 2. Prerequisites\n 31 | \n 32 | Ensure you have the following environments installed locally on your system:\n 33 | *   **Node.js**: `v18.x` or later (for running the Next.js frontend)\n 34 | *   **Python**: `v3.12.x` or later (for running the FastAPI backend)\n 35 | *   **pip**: Python package manager\n 36 | *   **SQLite3**: Installed on your system (typically comes bundled with Python)\n 37 | \n 38 | ---\n 39 | \n 40 | ## 3. Local Environment Variables Configuration\n 41 | \n 42 | To bridge the Next.js frontend and the FastAPI backend, you must establish environment templates in both repositories.\n 43 | \n 44 | ### 3.1. Create Backend Environment\n 45 | Copy the backend configuration template inside the `backend` folder:\n 46 | ```bash\n 47 | cp backend/.env.example backend/.env\n 48 | ```\n 49 | \n 50 | Your `backend/.env` file will look like this:\n 51 | ```env\n 52 | # GFF AI Local MVP Backend Configuration\n 53 | PROJECT_NAME=\"GFF AI Enterprise API\"\n 54 | API_V1_STR=\"/api/v1\"\n 55 | ENVIRONMENT=\"development\"\n 56 | DATABASE_URL=\"sqlite:///dev.db\"\n 57 | \n 58 | # Local JWT configuration\n 59 | JWT_SECRET=\"gff_ai_super_secret_local_key_for_jwt_tokens_2026\"\n 60 | ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES=11520  # 8 Days\n 61 | \n 62 | # Allowed CORS Origins\n 63 | CORS_ORIGINS=\"http://localhost:3000,http://127.0.0.1:3000\"\n 64 | FRONTEND_BASE_URL=\"http://localhost:3000\"\n 65 | ```\n 66 | \n 67 | ### 3.2. Create Frontend Environment\n 68 | Copy the frontend environment template in the project root:\n 69 | ```bash\n 70 | cp .env.example .env\n 71 | ```\n 72 | \n 73 | To enable active backend connectivity in the Next.js frontend, configure `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL` in the root `.env` to point to the local FastAPI port:\n 74 | ```env\n 75 | # API Integration\n 76 | NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8000/api/v1\n 77 | NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV=development\n 78 | NEXT_PUBLIC_PORTAL_UPLOADS_ENABLED=true\n 79 | ```\n 80 | \n 81 | *Note: If `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL` is omitted or commented out, the frontend gracefully falls back to its client-side mock handlers.*\n 82 | \n 83 | ---\n 84 | \n 85 | ## 4. Local Backend Setup & Installation\n 86 | \n 87 | To streamline development, root-level convenience scripts are provided in the master `package.json` file. These scripts manage virtual environments and package installations automatically.\n 88 | \n 89 | ### 4.1. Automatic Automated Installation (Recommended)\n 90 | From the **root directory** of the project, run:\n 91 | ```bash\n 92 | npm run backend:install\n 93 | ```\n 94 | This automated command:\n 95 | 1.  Enters the `backend/` directory.\n 96 | 2.  Creates a Python virtual environment (`venv/`) if it does not exist.\n 97 | 3.  Upgrades pip and installs all required dependencies from `backend/requirements.txt`.\n 98 | 4.  Generates a `.env` file from `.env.example` if it is missing.\n 99 | \n100 | ### 4.2. Manual Installation\n101 | If you prefer setting up the workspace manually, execute the following commands in your terminal:\n102 | ```bash\n103 | # Navigate to the backend directory\n104 | cd backend\n105 | \n106 | # Create virtual environment\n107 | python3 -m venv venv\n108 | \n109 | # Activate virtual environment\n110 | # On macOS / Linux:\n111 | source venv/bin/activate\n112 | # On Windows (CMD):\n113 | # venv\\Scripts\\activate.bat\n114 | \n115 | # Install package dependencies\n116 | pip install -r requirements.txt\n117 | ```\n118 | \n119 | ---\n120 | \n121 | ## 5. Database Initialization & Seeding\n122 | \n123 | The backend utilizes SQLite for multi-tenant data storage. The database tables are automatically initialized during FastAPI startup, but you must seed the tables to bootstrap enterprise development users and sample data.\n124 | \n125 | ### 5.1. Initialize & Seed Database\n126 | From the **root directory**, run:\n127 | ```bash\n128 | npm run backend:seed\n129 | ```\n130 | Alternatively, from the `backend` folder with your virtual environment active:\n131 | ```bash\n132 | python app/seed.py\n133 | ```\n134 | \n135 | This bootstraps a local SQLite file named `dev.db` inside the `backend/` directory and populates it with:\n136 | *   **Multi-tenant Client Accounts**: Apex Global, Chevron Corporation, and other reference enterprise enclaves.\n137 | *   **Projects & Sandboxes**: Dynamic multi-agent project pipelines mapped to roles and clients.\n138 | *   **Governance Audits**: Simulated compliance frameworks, compliance standards, and compliance tracking items.\n139 | *   **Secure Documents**: Legal records, service-level contracts, and ISO checklists.\n140 | *   **Billing Ledger & Invoices**: Compute epochs, consumption hours, and signed developer invoices.\n141 | *   **System Logs**: Dynamic audit logging structures.\n142 | \n143 | ### 5.2. Database Seeder Idempotency & Reset\n144 | *   **Idempotency**: Running `npm run backend:seed` repeatedly is fully idempotent. It verifies existing primary records before inserting, preventing duplicated keys or rows.\n145 | *   **Wiping the slate clean**: To hard reset the database (drop all tables, recreate schemas, and fresh seed), run the seeder script with the `--reset` flag:\n146 |     ```bash\n147 |     cd backend\n148 |     venv/bin/python app/seed.py --reset\n149 |     ```\n150 | \n151 | ---\n152 | \n153 | ## 6. Running the Services\n154 | \n155 | To test the end-to-end integration, you must run both the backend FastAPI server and the Next.js frontend simultaneously.\n156 | \n157 | ### 6.1. Launching the Backend (FastAPI)\n158 | From the **root directory**, run:\n159 | ```bash\n160 | npm run backend:dev\n161 | ```\n162 | This starts the Uvicorn ASGI server on `http://localhost:8000` with hot-reloading active.\n163 | \n164 | #### Active Ports & URLs:\n165 | *   **Service Root**: [http://localhost:8000](http://localhost:8000) (Automatically redirects to `/docs`)\n166 | *   **Interactive Swagger UI**: [http://localhost:8000/docs](http://localhost:8000/docs) (OpenAPI spec explorer)\n167 | *   **Dynamic Health Check**: [http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health](http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health)\n168 | \n169 | ### 6.2. Launching the Frontend (Next.js)\n170 | In a separate terminal window, from the **root directory**, run:\n171 | ```bash\n172 | npm run dev\n173 | ```\n174 | This starts the Next.js web application on [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000).\n175 | \n176 | \n177 | ---\n178 | \n179 | ## 7. Authenticating and Testing Portal/Admin Flows\n180 | \n181 | ### 7.1. Pre-Configured Developer Accounts & Roles\n182 | The seeder bootstraps five distinct users across different enterprise roles. You can log in using these credentials to test role-based access control (RBAC):\n183 | \n184 | | User Email | Assigned Role | Tenant Affiliation | Clear Password | Intended Test Flow |\n185 | | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n186 | | **gff_admin@gff.ai** | `gff_admin` | Platform Global | `password123` | Full administrative oversight, Client registry management, Audit logs, System-wide statistics. |\n187 | | **client_admin@apex.com** | `client_admin` | Apex Global | `password123` | Apex Client admin dashboard, Project pipelines, Billing summaries, Document review, Support. |\n188 | | **client_member@apex.com** | `client_member` | Apex Global | `password123` | Standard client operative view, Read-only billing, Read-write support tickets & compliance audits. |\n189 | | **admin@gff.ai** | `admin` | Platform Global | `gff_enterprise_admin_pass_2026` | Legacy administrative fallback authentication flow. |\n190 | | **client@chevron.com** | `client` | Chevron Corp | `chevron_secure_pass_2026` | Legacy single-tenant client dashboard authentication flow. |\n191 | \n192 | ### 7.2. Handshake Verification (End-to-End Test)\n193 | 1.  Open [http://localhost:3000/portal/login](http://localhost:3000/portal/login) (or `/admin/login`).\n194 | 2.  Observe the **Living Terminal Feed** on the right side. It will report:\n195 |     `[SYS] API backend service connection verified. Active mode: REST API.`\n196 | 3.  Enter credentials (e.g., `client_admin@apex.com` and `password123`).\n197 | 4.  Click **Initiate Secure Access**.\n198 | 5.  The system performs a cryptographic handshake, calling `/api/v1/auth/login` on the FastAPI server to retrieve a JWT, saves it in `localStorage` as `gff_api_token`, and routes you to the secure Client Dashboard (`/portal/dashboard`).\n199 | 6.  The backend validates the JWT token on every subsequent API call and scopes database queries based on the tenant (e.g., users logged in under Apex Global will not see Chevron Corporation's private projects).\n200 | \n201 | ---\n202 | \n203 | ## 8. Developer Troubleshooting Guide\n204 | \n205 | ### 8.1. Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) Issues\n206 | *   **Symptom**: The console shows `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` errors, or login handshakes fail with network/CORS block messages.\n207 | *   **Resolution**: \n208 |     1. Check your `backend/.env` file. Ensure `CORS_ORIGINS` is configured with the exact URL of your running frontend (usually `http://localhost:3000`).\n209 |     2. Multiple origins should be separated by commas without spaces, or formatted as a JSON list (e.g., `[\"http://localhost:3000\",\"http://127.0.0.1:3000\"]`).\n210 |     3. Restart your FastAPI backend server after updating `.env`.\n211 | \n212 | ### 8.2. Missing Database / SQLite Locks\n213 | *   **Symptom**: SQLite database errors like `OperationalError: no such table` or `database is locked` appear in the backend terminal logs.\n214 | *   **Resolution**:\n215 |     1. Verify that `dev.db` has been successfully created in the `backend/` directory.\n216 |     2. Run `npm run backend:seed` to initialize the SQLite database schema and seed user models.\n217 |     3. If SQLite reports a database lock, ensure there are no active, hanging Python processes or DB browsers holding a transaction open. Kill any zombie python processes:\n218 |        - macOS/Linux: `killall python python3` or `pkill uvicorn`\n219 |        - Windows: `taskkill /F /IM python.exe`\n220 | \n221 | ### 8.3. Invalid or Expired JWT Token\n222 | *   **Symptom**: Frontend queries immediately redirect back to login routes, or return `401 Unauthorized` responses in the developer console.\n223 | *   **Resolution**:\n224 |     1. Ensure the `JWT_SECRET` configured in your `backend/.env` matches what the backend loads. If the secret changed during server restarts, old tokens stored in your browser will become invalid.\n225 |     2. Clear your browser storage. Open the DevTools console and execute:\n226 |        ```javascript\n227 |        localStorage.clear();\n228 |        ```\n229 |     3. Re-authenticate via `/portal/login` to establish a fresh JWT token handshake.\n230 | \n231 | ### 8.4. Seed Rerun Failures\n232 | *   **Symptom**: Running the seeder yields unique constraint violations or integrity errors.\n233 | *   **Resolution**:\n234 |     1. The seeder is designed to be idempotent and update fields when keys match. However, if structural schema alterations were made to the SQLAlchemy models, migrations may conflict.\n235 |     2. Wipe the tables and run a clean bootstrap using the reset argument:\n236 |        ```bash\n237 |        npm run backend:seed -- --reset\n238 |        ```\n239 |        *(Note: The extra `--` passes the `--reset` option through npm to the python seed runner script).*\n240 | ","success":true},{"query":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/docs/PHASE_6_AWS_FINAL_SETUP.md","result":"  1 | # GFF AI Platform: Phase 6 AWS Production Deployment & Data Modeling Guide\n  2 | \n  3 | This document defines the enterprise AWS cloud migration strategy for the **GFF AI Platform** from the local Phase 5 sandbox. It specifies the exact schemas for three required DynamoDB tables, an S3 storage bucket, and the required environment parameters.\n  4 | \n  5 | ---\n  6 | \n  7 | ## 1. Cloud-Native Serverless Architecture\n  8 | \n  9 | ```\n 10 | +------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n 11 | |                               PHASE 6 ENTERPRISE AWS TOPOLOGY                                  |\n 12 | |  [ SECURE CLIENTS ] ==( HTTPS / TLS 1.3 )==> [ API GATEWAY ] ==> [ FASTAPI ON AWS LAMBDA ]    |\n 13 | |                                                                          |                     |\n 14 | |  [ S3 STORAGE BUCKET ] <--(Presigned URLs)-------------------------------+                     |\n 15 | |  (gff-portal-documents)                                                  v                     |\n 16 | |                                                                 [ AMAZON DYNAMODB ]            |\n 17 | |                                                                 - GFF_USERS                    |\n 18 | |                                                                 - GFF_CLIENTS                  |\n 19 | |                                                                 - GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS             |\n 20 | +------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n 21 | ```\n 22 | \n 23 | ---\n 24 | \n 25 | ## 2. Production DynamoDB Data Modeling\n 26 | \n 27 | Exactly **three** DynamoDB tables are used. Complex workspace and transactional entities are modeled inside a single-table architecture (`GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`) using custom Partition Keys (`PK`) and Sort Keys (`SK`).\n 28 | \n 29 | ### 2.1. Table Map Overview\n 30 | | Table Name | Partition Key (PK) | Sort Key (SK) | Global Secondary Index (GSI) | Purpose |\n 31 | | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n 32 | | **`GFF_USERS`** | `email` (String) | *None* | *None* | Global user registry and access credentials. |\n 33 | | **`GFF_CLIENTS`** | `client_id` (String) | *None* | *None* | Enterprise customer accounts. |\n 34 | | **`GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`** | `PK` (String) | `SK` (String) | `GSI1` (using `GSI1PK` & `GSI1SK`) | Multi-tenant workspace record store. |\n 35 | \n 36 | ### 2.2. Table Definition: `GFF_USERS`\n 37 | *   **Table Name**: `GFF_USERS`\n 38 | *   **Primary Key**: `email` (String)\n 39 | *   **Example Item**: `{\"email\": \"admin@client.com\", \"role\": \"admin\", \"client_id\": \"client_gff_01\"}`\n 40 | \n 41 | ### 2.3. Table Definition: `GFF_CLIENTS`\n 42 | *   **Table Name**: `GFF_CLIENTS`\n 43 | *   **Primary Key**: `client_id` (String)\n 44 | *   **Example Item**: `{\"client_id\": \"client_gff_01\", \"company_name\": \"Sovereign Logistics Corp\", \"tier\": \"ENTERPRISE\"}`\n 45 | \n 46 | ### 2.4. Single-Table Definition: `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`\n 47 | *   **Table Name**: `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`\n 48 | *   **Primary Key**: `PK` (String), `SK` (String)\n 49 | *   **GSI Name**: `GSI1` (using `GSI1PK` and `GSI1SK`)\n 50 | *   **Purpose**: Single-table design housing the 6 core operational models of the GFF AI Portal.\n 51 | \n 52 | #### Entity Mappings & Storage Patterns\n 53 | \n 54 | 1. **Projects**\n 55 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>`\n 56 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `METADATA`\n 57 |    - **Attributes**: `name`, `status`, `progress`, `budget`, `created_at`\n 58 | \n 59 | 2. **AI Operations**\n 60 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `AIOPS#<ops_id>`\n 61 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` (links to project) | **`GSI1SK`**: `AIOPS#<ops_id>`\n 62 |    - **Attributes**: `name`, `status`, `agent_count`, `runtime_seconds`, `cpu_usage`, `memory_usage`\n 63 | \n 64 | 3. **Documents Metadata**\n 65 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `DOC#<doc_id>`\n 66 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` (retrieves files by project) | **`GSI1SK`**: `DOC#<doc_id>`\n 67 |    - **Attributes**: `title`, `s3_key`, `file_size`, `category`, `uploaded_by`, `uploaded_at`\n 68 | \n 69 | 4. **Invoices Metadata**\n 70 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `INV#<invoice_id>`\n 71 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `BILLING_PERIOD#<year_month>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `INV#<invoice_id>`\n 72 |    - **Attributes**: `amount_usd`, `status`, `due_date`, `epochs_consumed`, `created_at`\n 73 | \n 74 | 5. **Support Tickets**\n 75 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `TICKET#<ticket_id>`\n 76 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `STATUS#<status_code>` (supports dashboard queues) | **`GSI1SK`**: `TICKET#<ticket_id>`\n 77 |    - **Attributes**: `subject`, `priority`, `status_text`, `assigned_to`, `created_at`\n 78 | \n 79 | 6. **Governance Items**\n 80 |    - **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `GOV#<gov_id>`\n 81 |    - **`GSI1PK`**: `STANDARD#<compliance_standard>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `GOV#<gov_id>`\n 82 |    - **Attributes**: `control_name`, `status`, `remediation_notes`, `assessed_at`\n 83 | \n 84 | ---\n 85 | \n 86 | ## 3. Cloud Object Storage Setup (Amazon S3)\n 87 | \n 88 | *   **Bucket Reference**: `gff-portal-documents-prod`\n 89 | *   **Security Configurations**:\n 90 |     *   **Block Public Access**: Enabled.\n 91 |     *   **Encryption at Rest**: Enforced using KMS customer-managed keys (SSE-KMS).\n 92 |     *   **Secure Transport**: Restricts transport to TLS 1.3/HTTPS.\n 93 |     *   **Presigned Access**: Frontend uploads/downloads via short-lived pre-signed URLs generated by Lambda (valid for 15 minutes).\n 94 | \n 95 | ---\n 96 | \n 97 | ## 4. Required Deployment Environment Keys\n 98 | \n 99 | ### 4.1. Next.js Frontend Keys (`.env.production`)\n100 | ```env\n101 | NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL=https://api.gff.ai/v1\n102 | NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV=production\n103 | NEXT_PUBLIC_PORTAL_UPLOADS_ENABLED=true\n104 | NEXT_PUBLIC_S3_BUCKET_NAME=gff-portal-documents-prod\n105 | ```\n106 | \n107 | ### 4.2. FastAPI AWS Backend Keys (`backend/prod.env` / Lambda Variables)\n108 | ```env\n109 | PROJECT_NAME=\"GFF AI Enterprise Cloud Engine\"\n110 | API_V1_STR=\"/api/v1\"\n111 | ENVIRONMENT=\"production\"\n112 | CORS_ORIGINS=\"https://portal.gff.ai,https://admin.gff.ai\"\n113 | FRONTEND_BASE_URL=\"https://portal.gff.ai\"\n114 | AWS_REGION=us-east-1\n115 | AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=production_aws_access_key_id\n116 | AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=production_aws_secret_access_key\n117 | DYNAMODB_USERS_TABLE=GFF_USERS\n118 | DYNAMODB_CLIENTS_TABLE=GFF_CLIENTS\n119 | DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TABLE=GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS\n120 | DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TYPE_INDEX=GSI1\n121 | S3_DOCUMENTS_BUCKET=gff-portal-documents-prod\n122 | S3_DOCUMENTS_PREFIX=clients\n123 | JWT_SECRET=production_cryptographically_secure_256_bit_signature_key_2026\n124 | ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES=1440\n125 | ```\n126 | \n127 | \n128 | ---\n129 | \n130 | ## 5. Seeded User Credentials (Final MVP Data)\n131 | \n132 | The system contains exactly **four** seeded user accounts covering the three standard RBAC roles (`gff_admin`, `client_admin`, `client_member`). All passwords, roles, and client associations are modeled to enable immediate high-fidelity secure testing.\n133 | \n134 | | Role | Email | Password | Associated Client | Notes |\n135 | | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n136 | | **`gff_admin`** | `gff_admin@gff.ai` | `password123` | *None* | Global platform administrator. Accesses the GFF Admin Panel. |\n137 | | **`client_admin`** | `client_admin@apex.com` | `password123` | `Apex Global Solutions` (ID: 1) | Enterprise client administrator. Full workspace management for Client 1. |\n138 | | **`client_member`** | `client_member@apex.com` | `password123` | `Apex Global Solutions` (ID: 1) | Client 1 standard user. Limited operational access inside Client 1 workspace. |\n139 | | **`client_member`** | `client@chevron.com` | `chevron_secure_pass_2026` | `Sovereign Logistics Corp` (ID: 2) | Client 2 standard user. Used to verify cross-tenant security and upload/download boundaries in smoke tests. |\n140 | \n141 | These credentials can be used both locally (via SQLite/mock fallbacks) and in the production cloud (AWS DynamoDB) once the environment is initialized and seeded using:\n142 | ```bash\n143 | npm run backend:seed\n144 | ```\n145 | \n146 | \n147 | \n148 | ---\n149 | \n150 | ## 6. Execution, Build, and Deployment Manual\n151 | \n152 | This section outlines the operational commands, deployment procedures, required environment parameters, and AWS production resources for launching the GFF AI Platform.\n153 | \n154 | ### 6.1. Backend Execution & Deployment Commands\n155 | \n156 | The backend is built as a cloud-ready FastAPI application that can be run locally using Uvicorn or deployed to AWS Lambda (e.g., using Mangum adapter) or AWS App Runner / Elastic Beanstalk.\n157 | \n158 | #### 1. Setup & Installation\n159 | To create the virtual environment and install all python dependencies, run:\n160 | ```bash\n161 | # From project root\n162 | npm run backend:install\n163 | \n164 | # Or from backend directory\n165 | cd backend\n166 | python3 -m venv venv\n167 | source venv/bin/activate\n168 | pip install -r requirements.txt\n169 | ```\n170 | \n171 | #### 2. Seed Database\n172 | To seed the database with multi-tenant workspace credentials, projects, operations, invoices, support tickets, and compliance logs:\n173 | ```bash\n174 | # From project root\n175 | npm run backend:seed\n176 | \n177 | # Or from backend directory with active virtual environment\n178 | cd backend\n179 | python app/seed.py\n180 | ```\n181 | \n182 | #### 3. Run Backend Start Command (Development/Production)\n183 | To launch the FastAPI ASGI server:\n184 | ```bash\n185 | # From project root (hot-reload enabled)\n186 | npm run backend:dev\n187 | \n188 | # From backend directory (standard FastAPI startup)\n189 | cd backend\n190 | venv/bin/uvicorn app.main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000\n191 | ```\n192 | *For production cloud environments (e.g., AWS App Runner or EC2), execute:*\n193 | ```bash\n194 | uvicorn app.main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000 --workers 4\n195 | ```\n196 | \n197 | #### 4. Backend Health & Smoke Checks\n198 | To execute complete RBAC, JWT, and multi-tenancy isolation tests:\n199 | ```bash\n200 | # From project root\n201 | npm run backend:check\n202 | \n203 | # Or from backend directory\n204 | cd backend\n205 | ./venv/bin/pytest app/test_backend_smoke.py\n206 | ./venv/bin/python app/test_security_utilities.py\n207 | ./venv/bin/python app/test_clients_api.py\n208 | ```\n209 | \n210 | ---\n211 | \n212 | ### 6.2. Next.js Frontend Execution & Build Commands\n213 | \n214 | The frontend is an enterprise-grade Next.js App Router workspace optimized for modern deployment platforms (Vercel, AWS Amplify, AWS ECS, or S3/CloudFront for static builds).\n215 | \n216 | #### 1. Frontend Build Command\n217 | To produce an optimized production-ready bundle:\n218 | ```bash\n219 | # From project root\n220 | npm run build\n221 | ```\n222 | This command compiles the TypeScript components, static assets, and App Router pages into the `.next` production distribution.\n223 | \n224 | #### 2. Frontend Start Command\n225 | To run the built production frontend server:\n226 | ```bash\n227 | # From project root\n228 | npm run start\n229 | ```\n230 | \n231 | #### 3. Frontend Development Command\n232 | To launch the local development hot-reloading server:\n233 | ```bash\n234 | # From project root\n235 | npm run dev\n236 | ```\n237 | \n238 | ---\n239 | \n240 | ### 6.3. Complete Production Environment Variables\n241 | \n242 | #### Backend Environment Variables\n243 | These variables must be configured in AWS Parameter Store, AWS Secrets Manager, or as environment variables on the hosting container/Lambda:\n244 | \n245 | | Variable Name | Required Value/Format | Purpose |\n246 | | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n247 | | `PROJECT_NAME` | `\"GFF AI Enterprise Cloud Engine\"` | API title metadata |\n248 | | `API_V1_STR` | `\"/api/v1\"` | API prefix path |\n249 | | `ENVIRONMENT` | `\"production\"` | Set runtime stage |\n250 | | `CORS_ORIGINS` | `https://portal.gff.ai,https://admin.gff.ai` | Allowed frontend domains (CORS compliance) |\n251 | | `FRONTEND_BASE_URL` | `https://portal.gff.ai` | Root URL of client-facing portal |\n252 | | `AWS_REGION` | `us-east-1` (or chosen region) | Target region for DynamoDB and S3 |\n253 | | `AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID` | *production_aws_access_key_id* | AWS IAM deployer credentials |\n254 | | `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY` | *production_aws_secret_access_key* | AWS IAM deployer secret |\n255 | | `DYNAMODB_USERS_TABLE` | `GFF_USERS` | DynamoDB user registry table |\n256 | | `DYNAMODB_CLIENTS_TABLE` | `GFF_CLIENTS` | DynamoDB enterprise client registry table |\n257 | | `DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TABLE` | `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS` | Multi-tenant operational records store |\n258 | | `DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TYPE_INDEX` | `GSI1` | Global Secondary Index for single-table queries |\n259 | | `S3_DOCUMENTS_BUCKET` | `gff-portal-documents-prod` | Secure client document storage |\n260 | | `S3_DOCUMENTS_PREFIX` | `clients` | File key namespace prefix |\n261 | | `JWT_SECRET` | *cryptographically_secure_256_bit_signature_key* | Cryptographic token signing secret |\n262 | | `ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES` | `1440` (24 hours) | Token lifespan limit |\n263 | \n264 | #### Frontend Environment Variables\n265 | These variables must be set in the build pipeline (e.g. Vercel dashboard, AWS Amplify console):\n266 | \n267 | | Variable Name | Required Value/Format | Purpose |\n268 | | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n269 | | `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL` | `https://api.gff.ai/v1` | URL pointing to the FastAPI gateway |\n270 | | `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV` | `production` | Deployment stage tag |\n271 | | `NEXT_PUBLIC_PORTAL_UPLOADS_ENABLED` | `true` | Enables upload features on Client Portal |\n272 | | `NEXT_PUBLIC_S3_BUCKET_NAME` | `gff-portal-documents-prod` | Target S3 bucket name |\n273 | \n274 | ---\n275 | \n276 | ### 6.4. AWS Production Cloud Resource Names\n277 | \n278 | Ensure the following exact resource names are created in your target AWS account to match the production configuration defaults:\n279 | \n280 | 1. **Amazon DynamoDB Tables**:\n281 |    - `GFF_USERS` (Primary Key: `email` [String])\n282 |    - `GFF_CLIENTS` (Primary Key: `client_id` [String])\n283 |    - `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS` (Primary Key: `PK` [String], Sort Key: `SK` [String], GSI: `GSI1` with PK `GSI1PK` [String] and SK `GSI1SK` [String])\n284 | \n285 | 2. **Amazon S3 Storage Bucket**:\n286 |    - `gff-portal-documents-prod` (Block All Public Access, KMS SSE-KMS Encryption, TLS 1.3 Secure Transport enforced)\n287 | \n288 | 3. **AWS IAM Execution Role Policy**:\n289 |    - Create a role with a minimum privilege boundary allowing full read/write access to the three DynamoDB tables above, and pre-signed URL generation access on the `gff-portal-documents-prod` S3 bucket.\n290 | ","success":true}],"durationMs":8}}
