ils**\n\nNow, I'm detailing the AWS infrastructure. I've listed the DynamoDB tables: `GFF_USERS`, `GFF_CLIENTS`, and `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`, including their primary keys and GSI details. I've also added the S3 bucket, `gff-portal-documents-prod`, and its security settings (Block All Public Access, SSE-KMS, TLS 1.3). Finally, I'm documenting all critical environment keys for both frontend and backend, clearly indicating their roles and example values to ensure a complete and useful Handoff.\n\n\n**Listing Environment Variables**\n\nI'm now detailing all crucial environment variables. I've noted allowed origins, the `FRONTEND_BASE_URL`, and regional AWS settings. I've also listed the DynamoDB table names and S3 bucket details. Finally, I included the JWT secret, access token expiry, and clarified the need for exactly four seeded MVP users in the setup.\n\n\n"}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T22:59:55.946Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"tool","toolName":"editor","toolCallId":"cs01e4bm","input":{"path":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/docs/FINAL_MVP_HANDOFF.md","new_text":"# GFF AI Platform: Final MVP Handoff Documentation\n\nThis document serves as the concise, practical handoff guide for deploying, running, and managing the **GFF AI Platform** (Next.js Frontend & FastAPI Backend).\n\n---\n\n## 1. Product Scope & Architectural Boundaries\n\n### 1.1. Core Platform Components\nThe GFF AI Platform is composed of two primary layers:\n1. **Next.js Frontend (App Router)**: A premium, Apple-like web interface providing client portals, administrator portals, public/educational pages, and interactive builders.\n2. **FastAPI Backend (REST API)**: A lightweight, high-performance API server managing authentication (JWT), role-based access control (RBAC), multi-tenant data structures, and dashboard operations.\n\n### 1.2. Crucial Scope Notice: GFF AI Tools\n> ⚠️ **IMPORTANT DESIGN BOUNDARY**:\n> All interactive **GFF AI Tools** inside the Build suite are **frontend-only, client-side mock configurations and interactive visual flows**. They are explicitly decoupled from the backend and do not call real live AI models, compile real local scripts, or connect to database persistence.\n> \n> These include:\n> *   **Sandbox / Agent Playgrounds** (`/build/sandbox`)\n> *   **Blueprint Generator** (`/build/blueprint`)\n> *   **ROI Calculator** (`/build/roi`)\n> *   **Proposal Builder / Intake** (`/build/proposal`)\n> *   **Agent Marketplace** (`/build/marketplace`)\n> *   **AI Readiness Assessment Framework** (`/build/assessment`)\n> *   **Foundry Studio** (`/build/foundry-studio`)\n> *   **Interactive Assistant / Talk** (`/build/talk`)\n>\n> All backend API integrations are reserved strictly for operational telemetry: User Profile Management, Client Workspace Handshakes, Multi-Tenant Projects, Real-Time Invoices/Epoch Telemetry, Support Ticket Queueing, S3 Document Metadata, and Compliance Governance Controls.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Production AWS Cloud Infrastructure\n\nTo transition from local SQLite development to production, the backend is engineered for a cloud-native AWS serverless topology (FastAPI on AWS Lambda/ECS connected to DynamoDB and S3).\n\n### 2.1. DynamoDB Data Modeling (Exactly 3 Tables)\nComplex relational mappings are collapsed into a high-performance single-table design for operational workspace items (`GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`), alongside dedicated identity tables.\n\n| Table Name | Partition Key (PK) | Sort Key (SK) | Global Secondary Index (GSI) | Purpose |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **`GFF_USERS`** | `email` (String) | *None* | *None* | Global user credentials, roles, and client ties. |\n| **`GFF_CLIENTS`** | `client_id` (String) | *None* | *None* | Enterprise customer entity directory. |\n| **`GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`** | `PK` (String) | `SK` (String) | `GSI1` (`GSI1PK` & `GSI1SK`) | Multi-tenant single-table workspace store. |\n\n#### Single-Table Entity Schema mappings (`GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS`)\n1. **Projects**:\n   * **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>`\n   * **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `METADATA`\n2. **AI Operations (Telemetry)**:\n   * **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `AIOPS#<ops_id>`\n   * **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `AIOPS#<ops_id>`\n3. **Documents Metadata**:\n   * **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `DOC#<doc_id>`\n   * **`GSI1PK`**: `PROJ#<project_id>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `DOC#<doc_id>`\n4. **Invoices / Billing**:\n   * **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `INV#<invoice_id>`\n   * **`GSI1PK`**: `BILLING_PERIOD#<year_month>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `INV#<invoice_id>`\n5. **Support Tickets**:\n   * **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `TICKET#<ticket_id>`\n   * **`GSI1PK`**: `STATUS#<status_code>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `TICKET#<ticket_id>`\n6. **Governance / Controls**:\n   * **`PK`**: `CLIENT#<client_id>` | **`SK`**: `GOV#<gov_id>`\n   * **`GSI1PK`**: `STANDARD#<compliance_standard>` | **`GSI1SK`**: `GOV#<gov_id>`\n\n### 2.2. Secure Object Storage (Amazon S3)\n*   **Bucket Name**: `gff-portal-documents-prod`\n*   **Access Paradigm**: Block All Public Access. Enforces Server-Side Encryption (SSE-KMS) and strict TLS 1.3 transport.\n*   **Operation**: The frontend interacts with files using short-lived (15-minute) secure Pre-signed URLs dynamically generated by the FastAPI backend using AWS SDK (Boto3).\n\n---\n\n## 3. Deployment & Operational Environment Variables\n\n### 3.1. Frontend Environment Variables (`.env.production`)\nSet these variables inside your frontend hosting provider (Vercel, AWS Amplify, or ECS):\n\n| Variable Name | Value / Format | Purpose |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL` | `https://api.gff.ai/v1` | Root URL pointing to the backend API Gateway |\n| `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_ENV` | `production` | Deployment phase / environment tag |\n| `NEXT_PUBLIC_PORTAL_UPLOADS_ENABLED` | `true` | Activates interactive upload features on portals |\n| `NEXT_PUBLIC_S3_BUCKET_NAME` | `gff-portal-documents-prod` | Target cloud storage bucket name |\n\n### 3.2. Backend Environment Variables (`backend/.env` / AWS Parameter Store)\nConfigure these values on AWS Lambda, ECS, or App Runner environments:\n\n| Variable Name | Value / Format | Purpose |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| `PROJECT_NAME` | `\"GFF AI Enterprise Cloud Engine\"` | API title metadata |\n| `API_V1_STR` | `\"/api/v1\"` | API URL prefix |\n| `ENVIRONMENT` | `\"production\"` | Runtime environment category |\n| `CORS_ORIGINS` | `https://portal.gff.ai,https://admin.gff.ai` | CORS whitelisted domains (comma-separated) |\n| `FRONTEND_BASE_URL` | `https://portal.gff.ai` | Root URL origin of the Client Portal |\n| `AWS_REGION` | `us-east-1` | AWS region of DynamoDB tables & S3 Bucket |\n| `AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID` | *production_aws_access_key_id* | AWS IAM execution credentials key ID |\n| `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY` | *production_aws_secret_access_key* | AWS IAM execution credentials secret key |\n| `DYNAMODB_USERS_TABLE` | `GFF_USERS` | DynamoDB User registry table name |\n| `DYNAMODB_CLIENTS_TABLE` | `GFF_CLIENTS` | DynamoDB Customer entity table name |\n| `DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TABLE` | `GFF_PORTAL_ITEMS` | Multi-tenant single-table store name |\n| `DYNAMODB_ITEMS_TYPE_INDEX` | `GSI1` | Global Secondary Index for single-table queries |\n| `S3_DOCUMENTS_BUCKET` | `gff-portal-documents-prod` | Secure S3 Document Storage bucket |\n| `S3_DOCUMENTS_PREFIX` | `clients` | File namespace key prefix |\n| `JWT_SECRET` | *cryptographically_secure_256_bit_signature_key* | Secret key for signing secure OAuth2 JWT tokens |\n| `ACCESS_TOKEN_EXPIRE_MINUTES` | `1440` | Expiration limit of auth tokens (24 Hours) |\n\n---\n\n## 4. Seeded MVP Credentials\n\nThe database contains exactly **four** pre-populated user accounts to facilitate instant RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) verification during local and staging evaluation.\n\n| Role | Email | Password | Associated Client Tenant | Platform Clearance |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **`gff_admin`** | `gff_admin@gff.ai` | `password123` | *None* (Global) | Accesses the Admin Dashboard (`/admin/dashboard`). |\n| **`client_admin`** | `client_admin@apex.com` | `password123` | `Apex Global Solutions` (ID: 1) | Admin for Tenant 1. Full view/edit of Client Workspace. |\n| **`client_member`** | `client_member@apex.com` | `password123` | `Apex Global Solutions` (ID: 1) | Standard user for Tenant 1. Operational-only workspace rights. |\n| **`client_member`** | `client@chevron.com` | `chevron_secure_pass_2026` | `Sovereign Logistics Corp` (ID: 2) | Standard user for Tenant 2. Used to test cross-tenant data isolation. |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Execution & Build Commands Reference\n\n### 5.1. Local Sandbox Environment Execution\nRun these commands from the root of the workspace during local development:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Install Backend Dependencies (FastAPI, SQLite, SQLite-Utils, Pytest)\nnpm run backend:install\n\n# 2. Setup SQLite Schema & Inject Multi-Tenant Seed Users/Items\nnpm run backend:seed\n\n# 3. Launch Local Hot-Reloading FastAPI Backend (Standard Port: 8000)\nnpm run backend:dev\n\n# 4. Launch Local Hot-Reloading Next.js Frontend (Standard Port: 3000)\nnpm run dev\n\n# 5. Run Security, RBAC & End-to-End API Integration Smoke Tests\nnpm run backend:check\n```\n\n### 5.2. Production Deployment Execution\nPrepare and run production workloads with these instructions:\n\n#### Next.js Frontend Production Build\nTo create an optimized production bundle and boot the production web server locally or in a container:\n```bash\n# Build the application\nnpm run build\n\n# Start the node runtime production server\nnpm run start\n```\n\n#### FastAPI Backend Production Launch\nTo boot the FastAPI server using multi-threaded Uvicorn workers in cloud hosting VMs, containers, or on-premises servers:\n```bash\n# Production launch command (4 workers, host bound to all network interfaces)\nuvicorn app.main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000 --workers 4\n```\n*(For Serverless AWS Lambda deployments, configure API Gateway to route to a Lambda containing the FastAPI application wrapped with the `Mangum` ASGI adapter).*\n"}}}
